==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Regal
<hw>Re"gal</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧"g⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>regalis</ets>, fr. <ets>rex</ets>, <ets>regis</ets>, a king. See
<er>Royal</er>, and cf. <er>Rajah</er>, <er>Realm</er>,
<er>Regalia</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a king; kingly; royal;
<as>as, <ex>regal</ex> authority, pomp, or sway</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>regal</xex> title.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He made a scorn of his <qex>regal</qex> oath.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Kingly; royal. See <er>Kingly</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Regal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Regal
<hw>Re"gal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧gale</ets>, It.
<ets>regale</ets>. CF. <er>Rigoll</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A
small portable organ, played with one hand, the bellows being worked
with the other, -- used in the sixteenth and seventeenth
centuries.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Regale</ent>⟦br⟧
